\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & (P+3)x^2 & -4x & +Q-5P-15 \\
\end{array}
\]Since $x^2 + 2x + 5$ is a factor of $x^4 + Px^2 + Q,$ we have $(P+3)x^2-4x+Q-5P-15=0$. We know that $x^2+2x+5$ is also a factor of this expression, so we can substitute $x^2+2x+5$ for $P$ to get $(P+3)(x^2+2x+5)-4x+(Q-5P-15)=0$. Simplifying this gives $P+3=0$ and $Q-5P-15=0$, so $P=-3$ and $Q=0$. Thus, $P+Q=\boxed{-3}$.
